As for the month and the day, Clement of Alexandrial speaks of calculations which result in fixing these as the 18th or 19th of April, or even as the 29th of May. But these were private calculations upon which no festival observance could be made to depend. The book called De Pascha Oomputus, put forth in 243, either in Africa or in Italy, states that our Lord was born on the 28th of March.2 Those who proposed such figures evidently knew nothing of the existence of the festival of the Nativity.
